19 Vidi conte Orso e l’anima divisa 20 dal corpo suo per astio e per inveggia, 21 com’ e’ dicea, non per colpa commisa;
22 Pier da la Broccia dico; e qui proveggia, 23 mentr’ è di qua, la donna di Brabante, 24 sì che però non sia di peggior greggia.

query.result:
25 As I was free from all those 26 shadows who pray only if others pray, 27 so that becoming holy might fall to them,
28 I began: «It seems to me that you deny me, 29 O my light, expressed in some text 30 that decrees heavenly prayers bend;
31 and these people pray only of this: 32 would therefore their hope be vain, 33 or is your saying not clear to me?».

query.prompt:
Please translate each line literally into English.

34 Ed elli a me: «La mia scrittura è piana;
35 e la speranza di costor non falla,
36 se ben si guarda con la mente sana;

37 ché cima di giudicio non s’avvalla
38 perché foco d’amor compia in un punto
39 ciò che de’ sodisfar chi qui s’astalla;

40 e là dov’ io fermai cotesto punto,
41 non s’ammendava, per pregar, difetto,
42 perché ’l priego da Dio era disgiunto.

query.result:
34 And he to me: “My writing is plain;
35 and the hope of these does not fail,
36 if one looks well with a healthy mind;

37 because the peak of judgment does not bend
38 because the fire of love completes in one point
39 what of satisfying those who here stay;

40 and there where I fixed that point,
41 one could not amend, through praying, defect,
42 because the prayer was separated from God.”

46 I do not know if you understand: I speak of Beatrice;
47 you will see her above, on the peak
48 of this mountain, laughing and happy.

52 “We will proceed with this day forward,”
53 he responded, “as much as we can now;
54 but the fact is of another form than to stay.”

76 Ah, servant Italy, dwelling of sorrow, 77 ship without a pilot in great tempest, 78 not lady of provinces, but brothel!
79 That noble soul was so quick, 80 only for the sweet sound of her land, 81 to make for her citizen there a feast;
82 and now within you do not stay without war 83 your living ones, and each one gnaws at the other 84 of that which a wall and a ditch enclose.

130 Many have justice in heart, and late shoots
131 to not come without counsel to the bow;
132 but your people has it on the top of the mouth.

133 Many refuse the common burden;
134 but your people solicitous responds
135 without calling, and cries: “I take it upon myself!”

136 Now makes you happy, because you have good waves;
137 you rich, you with peace and you with sense!
138 If I say the truth, the effect does not hide it.
